Frailty of the Flat World
The world is flat!
Columnist Thomas Friedman says this. Friedman chose this provocative title for his best-selling book to make people aware of the astonishing impact of technology on the world economy.
Distances are shortening.
Geographic barriers can no longer easily provide protection.
Manufacturing workers and high-tech professionals in Europe and the United States all have to face the challenge of global competition.
When Western consumers call local companies, the employees they speak to may very well be far away in India.
Skeptics point out the limits of Friedman's metaphor.
As someone said, the world is not flat, but "uneven."
The topographic map of global economic activity shows peaks of prosperity and valleys of deprivation.
Not only that, distance has far from lost its significance.
Even for neighboring countries with lower tariff barriers, such as Canada and the United States, domestic trade is still much greater than cross-border trade.
Although Seattle and Vancouver are geographically close, Vancouver's trade with Toronto, which is farther away, is much greater than its trade with nearby Seattle.
Despite such criticisms, Friedman still put forward an important point.
Globalization can be defined as mutual dependence between different continents, its history is as long as human history, witnessing migration of races and religions, as well as the ancient trade along the Silk Road between medieval Europe and Asia.
But today's globalization is different; it develops faster and is more deeply integrated.
In 1868, after the first transatlantic telegraph cable was laid, Europe and the United States could communicate within a minute.
In 1919, economist John Maynard Keynes described British people living in London ordering goods from all over the world by telephone and then waiting at home for them to arrive in the afternoon.
However, Keynes's British people were a special case of the extremely wealthy.
Today, hundreds of millions of people around the world can buy goods from all over the world at local supermarkets.
Similarly, 20 years ago, there was an immediate global communication, but it exceeded the affordability of most people economically.
Now, almost anyone can walk into an internet café and gain the ability that was previously only accessible to the government, multinational corporations, and a few individuals or institutions with large budgets.
The significant decrease in the costs of computing, communication, and transportation has made technology increasingly widespread.
Just ten years ago, two-thirds of internet users were concentrated in the United States.
But today, the proportion of internet users in the United States among global users is less than a quarter.
Knowledge is power, and today the number of people who have access to information has reached an all-time high in human history.
Non-state actors now possess capabilities that were once exclusively held by governments.
The position of the nation-state as the primary subject of world politics will not change for now, but it must learn to share this massive stage with more participants, including institutions like the Oxford饥荒救济委员会 (Oxford Food Relief Committee), celebrities like Bono, and transnational terrorist networks like Al-Qaeda.
However, this process of flattening is reversible.
Similar situations have occurred before.
In 1914, the world economy was highly integrated, but over the following 30 years, economic interdependence among countries continuously declined.
It wasn't until 1970 that the global economy recovered to the level of integration it had previously known, and even then, it was still blocked by the Iron Curtain.
The First World War was the catalyst for this reversal; during the two World Wars and the global Cold War, people witnessed a decline in economic globalization and an increase in military globalization.
This reflected the deeper issues caused by 19th-century economic development, such as domestic inequality.
Politics failed to adapt to economic development, resulting in abnormal ideologies—fascism and communism—achieving great influence. This pathological development concept caused fragmentation within nations and around the world.
The welfare state system in the West after World War II created a safety net for those harmed by economic changes, encouraging them to accept the benefits brought by international economic interdependence.
Some analysts believe that China's role today is very similar to Germany's in the 20th century.
They are rising powers troubled by domestic inequality, constantly developing in the direction of nationalism, challenging the dominant powers, and eventually triggering world wars that reverse the progress of economic globalization.
Although the economies of the United States and China are highly interdependent today, the economies of Britain and Germany before 1914 were no different.
But such reasoning is incomplete.
After 1900, Germany's industrial production had already surpassed that of Britain.
However, even if China maintains this high growth rate, its economy is unlikely to catch up with the United States within at least 20 years.
The greater threat to the flat world may come from non-state and transnational forces unleashed by the spread of technology.
On September 11, 2001, a non-state network killed more Americans in an unannounced attack than the Japanese government's attack on Pearl Harbor in 1941.
I call this phenomenon the privatization of war.
If such forces gained access to nuclear weapons and biological materials, the world would undergo a complete transformation.
At that time, the movement of people and goods across borders would become more difficult.
If the above-mentioned forces disrupted the oil exports from the Persian Gulf, which accounts for two-thirds of the world's oil reserves, a global economic depression similar to that of the 1930s could further strengthen the forces of protectionism.
Technology and policy are the two major drivers of globalization.
So far, policies have further reinforced the flattening effects of technology.
As the world's largest economic entity, the United States has taken the lead in promoting policies to remove obstacles.
However, the events described above may reverse this policy.
Some critics of globalization might welcome such an outcome.
But such an outcome, as we saw after 1914, would lead to the worst conditions in two areas—namely, the reversal of the economic globalization trend of spreading technology and power, while the negative consequences of military and ecological globalization would be further entrenched, such as war, terrorism, climate change, and the spread of infectious diseases.
If that were the case, the flat world would become a desert.
